kb:content-safety rdf:type  ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Content Safety" ;
               kpred:has-status   "production" ;
               kpred:principle    "Ethics AND morals, not just law. Laws vary across borders and legality is a floor, not a ceiling — Reckons.AI applies a baseline ethical standard (no incitement, no hate, no sexualization of minors) regardless of local legality. Some things simply should not be broadcast publicly." ;
               kpred:principle    "Responsibility model: Reckons.AI is a neutral, local-first TOOL — the user owns and is responsible for the content they create and share. The app makes a good-faith EFFORT to protect users and keep the worst content off the public web, but is not responsible for user-generated content. Documented for humans in SAFETY.md (repo root)." ;
               kpred:description  "Ethics preamble in all LLM prompts (ETHICS_PREAMBLE, src/lib/safety/content-policy.ts). Content classifier (blocked/mature/none) filters blocked content on ingest; mature is flagged. Export advisory headers warn recipients. Local-first: nothing leaves the device unless the user connects an integration." ;
               kpred:has-part     kb:publish-safety-gate ;
               kpred:has-part     kb:verified-badge .

kb:publish-safety-gate rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Publish Safety Gate" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F66" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:content-safety ;
               kpred:principle    "PRIVATE sharing is the user's to manage (handing someone a .ttl is like emailing a file — the app doesn't police it). PUBLIC publishing to the open web is GATED: make a good-faith effort to block publicly sharing graphs that incite violence or are otherwise illegal or hateful." ;
               kpred:principle    "GATE ONLY WHAT WE CARRY (Option C, 2026-07-12 — see kb:adult-content-policy). The gate refuses to CARRY, it never refuses to LET THE USER HAVE: user-export is always available, whatever the graph contains. It also asks NO QUESTION — no purpose declaration, no attestation, no terms to accept — because a gate that accepts an explanation is a gate anyone can talk their way past." ;
               kpred:scope        "Refuses at mediated distribution: (1) Tier 1 always — minors, NCII, sextortion/blackmail, incitement, mass-casualty weapons; (2) Tier 2 adult content — declined with a plain 'export it and self-host' message, no judgment and no appeal. Tier 3 passes." ;
               kpred:description  "Before a graph is published to the open web (publishSiteToGitHub / any public target), run it through the same classifier (classifyStatement / filterBlockedStatements) and REFUSE to publish when blocked content is present — with a clear explanation, not a silent drop. Distinct from the existing export ADVISORY (which warns): the publish gate BLOCKS. Also leans on the natural barrier — Reckons.AI hosts nothing, so public publishing requires the user's OWN domain/hosting/file-sharing (Cloudflare, GitHub Pages, a Git host), which limits casual/anonymous abuse and makes the publisher accountable through their own provider. Builds on content-safety; extends site-export.ts." ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:gates        kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:gates        kb:published-ttl ;
               kpred:gates        kb:published-graph-exchange ;
               kpred:gates        kb:share-links ;
               kpred:gates        kb:read-only-guest ;
               kpred:gates        kb:kb-publication .

# -- Data egress model (2026-07-12) ---------------------------------------------
# The audit asked a question the graph could not answer: "which features send user
# data off-device?" — the single most important privacy question for a local-first,
# privacy-by-default app. It was unanswerable because egress was never modeled.
#
# THE LINE IS EXPORT vs DISTRIBUTION, not private vs public:
#
#   EXPORT is a RIGHT. Plain-text/TTL export of your own graph to your own disk is
#   NEVER blocked. Blocking it would be data lock-in, and it is futile anyway — the
#   graph sits in IndexedDB and can be read out regardless. Advisory header only.
#
#   DISTRIBUTION is a PRIVILEGE. When Reckons.AI is the INTERMEDIARY that hands
#   content to someone else — publish to the web, a share link, the exchange, a guest
#   view, a third-party sync — the app is participating in delivery, so it gates.
#
# What the user does with an exported file afterwards is their business (F66's
# principle, SAFETY.md). The gate binds where WE are in the loop, and nowhere else —
# claiming otherwise would be overclaiming a control we cannot exercise.

kb:data-egress-model rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label   "Data egress model (export is a right, distribution is a privilege)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:content-safety ;
               kpred:description  "Classifies every feature by where user data can travel, so the graph can answer 'what leaves the device, and are we the one carrying it?'. kpred:data-egress takes one of: none (stays in IndexedDB); user-export (plain text/TTL to the user's own disk — a RIGHT, never blocked, advisory header only, no lock-in); mediated-distribution (Reckons.AI is the intermediary delivering content to a third party or the open web — publish, share link, exchange, guest view — BLOCKING gate); third-party-service (an opt-in integration's servers, e.g. Drive/n8n/GitHub — gated by explicit user connect + advisory, blocking for public targets). Only mediated-distribution and third-party-service require kpred:gated-by; user-export must NOT be gated, and a lint that demanded one would be a bug." ;
               kpred:egress-value "none" ;
               kpred:egress-value "user-export" ;
               kpred:egress-value "mediated-distribution" ;
               kpred:egress-value "third-party-service" ;
               kpred:principle    "Export is a RIGHT: the user's graph is the user's, in a plain, portable, non-proprietary format. Reckons.AI never withholds a user's own data from them, whatever it contains." ;
               kpred:principle    "Distribution is a PRIVILEGE: when the app is the intermediary handing content to someone else, it is a participant in that delivery and gates accordingly. Once a file has left as a user-export, what happens next is the user's responsibility, not a control we pretend to have." ;
               kpred:invariant    "data-egress in {mediated-distribution, third-party-service} => kpred:gated-by is required, and the gate's lifecycle status must be >= the gated feature's status." ;
               kpred:invariant    "data-egress = user-export => NO blocking gate. Advisory only (scanForExportAdvisory)." .

# -- Adult content policy (F66.1) — DECIDED 2026-07-12: OPTION C -----------------
# The goal: DO NOT block a romance author writing explicit fiction, while refusing to
# help distribute abuse material.
#
# WE GATE ONLY WHAT WE CARRY. Reckons.AI provides no mediated distribution channel for
# adult content. Write it, keep it, export it, self-host it — all unimpeded. We simply
# will not be the one handing it to strangers. That is a refusal to CARRY, not a
# refusal to LET YOU HAVE, and the difference is the whole policy.
#
# The decisive property of Option C: it deletes the gameable attestation entirely.
# There is NO purpose declaration, NO T&C tier-unlock, NO context field — because
# CONTEXT IS NEVER AN INPUT TO THE GATE. Nobody can talk their way past a gate that
# asks no question. The blackmailer who wraps their material in a plausible paragraph
# about their novel has nothing to wrap it in. It also means no accounts, no server, no
# PII, no retention duty, and no age-verification exposure — the app stays local-first.

kb:adult-content-policy rdf:type ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Adult content policy (gate only what we carry)" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F66.1" ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:publish-safety-gate ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:data-egress-model ;
               kpred:decided      "Option C (2026-07-12): Reckons.AI offers NO mediated distribution channel for adult content. Authoring, storage, and user-export are entirely unimpeded; only mediated distribution is refused." ;
               kpred:description  "Applies at MEDIATED DISTRIBUTION only — never at authoring, never at storage, never at user-export. TIER 1 (refused everywhere we are in the loop, and refused at generation by the ETHICS_PREAMBLE): sexualization of minors; non-consensual intimate content of real people; sextortion/blackmail; incitement; mass-casualty weapons instructions. TIER 2 ADULT (explicit fiction between adults, graphic fictional violence): NOT MEDIATED. The publish gate declines to carry it and says so plainly — 'Reckons.AI won't publish this for you; export it and host it yourself.' No moral judgment, no accusation, no appeal process, and crucially no questionnaire to game. TIER 3: mediated freely. A false positive costs the user one export and a self-host, so over-blocking is cheap; that is what makes this workable with an imperfect classifier." ;
               kpred:principle    "Gate only what we carry. Export is a right; distribution is a privilege; we decline to be the intermediary for adult material rather than pretending to adjudicate it." ;
               kpred:principle    "Context is never an input to the gate. A gate that accepts a stated purpose is a gate anyone can talk their way past — so we ask nothing, and there is nothing to lie about." ;
               kpred:principle    "Tier 1 is principled, not squeamish: it is exactly the set where the harm lands on a THIRD PARTY WHO DID NOT CONSENT. Fiction between consenting adults has no victim; content aimed at a real person does." ;
               kpred:remaining    "Tier 1 detection should target the COERCION SIGNATURE (a real identifiable person + intimate material + a threat + a demand), which is structural and detectable independently of explicitness — unlike 'classify smut', which simultaneously over-blocks romance authors and under-blocks abuse." ;
               kpred:known-gap    "The current classifier (content-policy.ts MATURE_PATTERNS) matches DESCRIPTIONS of content — the literal phrases 'sexually explicit', 'pornographic' — not content itself. Actual explicit prose is not detected, while a triple merely SAYING a document is erotic gets flagged. It must not be described as a content filter until rewritten." ;
               kpred:consequence  "No accounts, no server, no attestation records, no PII retention, no age-verification surface. The traceability problem in COUNSEL-BRIEF.md §6 is DISSOLVED rather than solved: there is nothing to trace because there is no claim to lie about." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:publish-safety-gate .

kb:verified-badge rdf:type  ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label   "Verified Badge" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F67" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:content-safety ;
               kpred:description  "A positive trust signal: a verified badge for a reviewed, accountable publisher or graph — distinct from the anonymous, un-hosted default. Rewards good-faith authors who put their name/domain behind a published graph, and gives readers a signal of provenance. Open question: what does verification attest (identity? a content review? a stable domain?) and who issues it." .

