kb:docs-pipeline rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Docs graph Publishing Pipeline" ;
               kpred:has-status   "functional" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F27.2" ;
               kpred:description  "The docs knowledge graphs (static/starter-guide.ttl, the hub with hnav:order-sequenced leap nodes, plus the nine static/docs-*.ttl sub-graphs: triples-rdf, llm, use-cases, features, integrations-tech, tips-security, timeline-ecosystem, architecture, testing) are the source of truth for the 'generated' sections of the published /docs site. scripts/docs-pages.ts (npm run docs:pages) parses the TTLs with n3, turns each qualifying entity (any subject typed under urn:kbase:type/, excluding each sub-graph's urn:reckons:docs/nav/ back-to-hub stub) into a WebPage, and writes content/<section>/<slug>.md via pageToMarkdown — so the output round-trips through scripts/md-align.ts exactly like Sveltia-authored pages. Every generated page carries generated: \"docs-kb\" in its frontmatter (page:generated / PAGE_GENERATED in src/lib/rdf/page.ts); regeneration is idempotent and prunes any previously-generated file whose entity was removed from the TTLs, but never touches a file without that tag. An entity asserted in both the hub (a lightweight 'summary' stub, kept inline for the hub's own story/graph view) and a sub-graph (the fuller definition) is owned by the sub-graph; slugs are disambiguated by section suffix when two distinct entities share a local name across sections. Generated ~236 pages across 10 sections on first run." ;
               kpred:tooling      "CI (.github/workflows/kb-watch.yml) runs scripts/docs-pages.ts on every push/PR: pushes to main that produce a diff are committed back as github-actions[bot] ('docs: regenerate content from docs graphs'); PRs only report the drift in the job summary. The generator's own idempotency is the loop guard — a regeneration commit produces zero further diff, so it doesn't retrigger itself." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:webpage-entity ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing .

kb:gp-authoring rdf:type     ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label    "Docs authoring surface" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:description  "Website/docs settings live on the Graph page (the manage/switch surface). Reckoning (Situation-Target-Proposal) is a first-class way to draft/edit page content; AI-generated content is directly editable in the graph before it becomes a page." ;
               kpred:decision     "No markdown-to-TTL back-propagation (decided 2026-07-03). Graph edits happen in the app or directly on the TTL files via the local workspace folder linked in Graph settings; Sveltia is only for non-generated content. Edits to generated pages are overwritten by the next regeneration — by design." ;
               kpred:has-status   "planned" .

kb:sveltia-cms-setup rdf:type ktype:Concept ;
               rdfs:label    "Sveltia CMS — Setup (GitHub OAuth)" ;
               kpred:part-of      kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:description  "Wire the /admin content manager. The CMS entry (static/admin/index.html) + config (static/admin/config.yml) ship in the app and are served at Reckons.AI/admin. GitHub login uses sveltia-cms-auth, a small Cloudflare Worker." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "1. Deploy sveltia-cms-auth: github.com/sveltia/sveltia-cms-auth (Cloudflare Worker reckons-sveltia-cms-auth, mapped to admin.reckons.ai). DONE." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "2. Create a GitHub OAuth App: Settings > Developer settings > OAuth Apps. Homepage https://reckons.ai; Authorization callback URL https://admin.reckons.ai/callback. MANUAL — a human must do this in the GitHub UI." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "3. Set the worker's GITHUB_CLIENT_ID / GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET vars and ALLOWED_DOMAINS to the OAuth App credentials. ALLOWED_DOMAINS is a comma-separated allowlist (`*` matches one subdomain level); it is 'reckons.ai,*.reckons-ai.pages.dev' so the production custom domain AND the dev branch alias + hashed preview deploys (dev.reckons-ai.pages.dev, <hash>.reckons-ai.pages.dev) can all authenticate. TOOLED — paste the OAuth App's Client ID/Secret into SVELTIA_GITHUB_CLIENT_ID / SVELTIA_GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET / SVELTIA_ALLOWED_DOMAINS in .env (see .env.example), then run scripts/sveltia-auth-secrets.sh, which pushes them to the worker via `wrangler secret put`. VERIFIED 2026-07-09: GET /auth?provider=github&site_id=dev.reckons-ai.pages.dev (and a preview hash) both 302 to github.com/login/oauth/authorize; a disallowed domain does not." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "4. backend.base_url in static/admin/config.yml points at https://admin.reckons.ai. DONE." ;
               kpred:setup-step   "5. Visit https://reckons.ai/admin/ and Login with GitHub" ;
               kpred:alt          "Local editing without the worker: Sveltia has no proxy-server backend (@sveltia/cms-proxy-server does not exist on npm) and ignores local_backend (a Decap-only option). On localhost it auto-offers \"Work with Local Repository\" (File System Access API, Chromium-family browsers only) with no config change needed." ;
               kpred:note         "/admin is a standalone static page, so the app's strict CSP does not apply; Sveltia reaches api.github.com and the worker directly." ;
               kpred:note         "RESOLVED (2026-07-02): the earlier bare-404 readiness finding was a missing route — the worker was deployed with the correct sveltia-cms-auth code but had workers.dev previews disabled and no custom domain attached. Fixed by attaching admin.reckons.ai as a Workers custom domain via the Cloudflare API (PUT /accounts/{id}/workers/domains). OAuth App credentials pushed via scripts/sveltia-auth-secrets.sh. Verified: GET /auth?provider=github&site_id=reckons.ai returns 302 to github.com/login/oauth/authorize. Setup steps 1-4 complete; only step 5 (login smoke test at reckons.ai/admin/) remains." ;
               kpred:note         "static/admin/index.html now loads a version-pinned Sveltia bundle (@sveltia/cms@0.169.1) instead of an unpinned \"latest\" CDN URL, so upgrades are deliberate. static/media/ (config.yml media_folder) was missing and has been created with a .gitkeep." ;
               kpred:note         "RESOLVED (2026-07-02): Pages collection listed zero entries after login, even though content/docs/welcome.md and content/releases/v0-1-0.md exist on main with matching frontmatter. Root cause: Sveltia CMS does not implement Decap/Netlify's `nested` collection option at all (confirmed against the pinned @sveltia/cms@0.169.1 bundle and its docs — nested collections are tracked for a future 2.0 release). The committed config's `nested: { depth: 4 }` was silently ignored, so the folder collection fell back to scanning only the immediate content/ directory and found nothing, since both pages live one level down (content/docs/, content/releases/). Fix: replaced `nested: { depth: 4 }` with `path: '{{fields.section | slugify}}/{{fields.slug}}'` in static/admin/config.yml and in the generated-config string sveltiaConfig() in src/lib/publish/site-export.ts (kept in lockstep). `path` is the option Sveltia does support for subfoldered entries: it recursively discovers existing files matching the template and places new ones, with no per-entry index file required. The `slugify` filter mirrors contentPath()'s `slugify(page.section)` so the folder segment matches what's on disk (e.g. section \"Docs\" -> content/docs/). Verified against the real pinned Sveltia bundle via Playwright + the CMS's built-in `test-repo` backend (OPFS-backed, no GitHub auth needed): with the original `nested` config the console logged \"Nested collections are not yet supported in Sveltia CMS\" and the collection showed 0 entries on the exact same seeded files; with the `path` fix it showed 2 entries (Welcome, Reckons.AI v0.1.0) with correct titles/status. Also verified creating a new page (title \"Test Page\", section \"Sandbox\") through the real CMS UI wrote content/sandbox/test-page.md, matching site-export.ts's contentPath() layout exactly. Note: Sveltia's own frontmatter serialization (quoting style, empty-string fields) differs cosmetically from pageToMarkdown()'s canonical form, so scripts/md-align.ts correctly flags freshly CMS-saved files as drifted until they are re-exported from the graph — this is by design, not a bug." .

# -- Publishing v2 / Static Site Generator (F55) --------------------------------
# Grow F27 graph-publishing from a docs/markdown pipeline into a real, themeable
# static site generator: style defined in the graph, cloud file storage beyond
# GitHub (Google Drive, GitLab), GitLab as a first-class GitHub alternative, and
# richer page/route authoring. Absorbs the standalone SveltiaWebsiteTemplate and
# Gitlab-SveltiaWebsiteTemplate projects — uniting web-content editing with the
# graph editing experience. Raised 2026-07-10; needs its own planning pass.

kb:publishing-v2 rdf:type    ktype:Feature ;
               rdfs:label    "Publishing v2 — Static Site Generator" ;
               kpred:feature-id   "F55" ;
               kpred:has-status   "speculative" ;
               kpred:description  "Turn Reckons.AI publishing (F27) into a full, themeable static site generator: the site's look, structure, and file assets are all describable in the graph, and non-docs pages (landing, detail) are first-class. Absorb the local SveltiaWebsiteTemplate + Gitlab-SveltiaWebsiteTemplate work so web-content editing rides on the knowledge-graph editing experience." ;
               kpred:depends-on   kb:graph-publishing ;
               kpred:relates-to   kb:workspace-sync .

kb:gp-style-system rdf:type  ktype:Feature ;
